6.3 Required Source Code Changes
To actually use memory-safe networking through the usnet_sockets library I argued for a source
code approach in Section 4.2. Redirecting the libc functions or syscalls at runtime for any binary
would be the other approach. This section evaluates which changes to the code base are needed for
a Rust project to use memory-safe userspace networking with usnet_sockets.
As example I chose the HTTP library tiny-http [149] and the web framework rouille which uses
tiny-http [150]. A concrete implementation of a web service could use rouille and, thus, indirectly uses tiny-http. When such a web service is installed by building it from source with Rust‚Äôs
cargo install command, then ideally a build feature Ô¨Çag should be enough to enable memorysafe userspace networking. The following steps describe which changes were needed to achieve
this.
Since tiny-http directly uses the Rust standard library socket types I modiÔ¨Åed the import statements
to use the compatible socket types in usnet_socket. These modiÔ¨Åcations should not be the default
for tiny-http and, therefore, were guarded by a feature Ô¨Çag called ‚Äúusnet‚Äù. Now the library either uses the kernel network stack or the userspace network stack depending on the build feature
Ô¨Çag. Listing 6.1 lists these changes. When porting the library I Ô¨Årst needed to add a feature to
usnet_sockets which I Ô¨Årst saw as low priority. I needed to add support for cloning TCP streams
as well as closing the TX or RX half of the connection. In smoltcp, however, the RX half alone
cannot be closed without the TX half since it is impossible with TCP to forbid the sender to send
more. I decided to ignore such a close action for the RX half. A solution would be to keep a separate
RX-closed state in the TcpStream socket type of usnet_sockets to forbid future read calls.

